text: Kind of different for me at the very beginning. I'm friends with two guys I used to work with, and they started a Bitcoin mining business, which is today one of the world's largest mining operations. And in 2012, one of them approached me, a friend said, look, Moritz, you have to buy some of that Bitcoin just to get on the boat. And I dismissed it because back then it was like it had the narrative of being illegal and money laundering and only bad things happening, circumventing the central banks, disrupting the system. So I wanted to stay away from it. And then a year later, 2013, I meet him again. We have a coffee and I gave in and I just put a little bit of money. Really, very little money into Bitcoin. I didn't know anything about cold wallets or cold storage, none of that stuff. So I think I probably bought it on Bitfinex or Bitstamp and it's in a hot wallet. Then we started. We started mining. So we worked with him and we got some mining capacity from him. Ethereum came in 2015. Then 2016, I meet Moritz. There's some movement in prices. The space is going higher. We're now approaching this ICO craziness. There's more tokens and more coins popping up. I mean, remember like 2013, you had Bitcoin and probably Monero and Litecoin and Dash and a few others. But it wasn't like today where there's like thousands and thousands. Thousands of tokens and coins and it's impossible to really keep track of the entire space. It was limited. But when Ethereum happened, that obviously unlocked the smart contracting and all the applications that you can run on a smart contract platform such as Ethereum, unlocked DeFi. And today it's unlocking Web3 and Metaverse and play to earn and game to earn and walk to earn. And this is an exponentially growing space. And then the CME got in in 2018 with the futures contracts. New exchanges. New trading venues popped up. FTX, for instance, one of the largest ones today. Interactive Brokers is now offering crypto trading. Coinbase IPO. Look, I mean, this is a fast growing market and it created a lot of trading opportunities for us. You can trade these markets from a trend following point of view. And I do that. And you can also see other inefficiencies that are exploitable in these prices. And we've talked about the basis. The Bitcoin and Ethereum futures. The futures basis. The funding basis, which is now relatively unattractive. Maybe it'll be a bit more attractive in the future. I don't know that. But two years ago, that basis was 30, 40, sometimes even higher than 40%. So you have a cash and carry trade staring you in the eye where you can make 40% per year. And it's kind of like you have to do it. But figuring out how to best do that trade, that is kind of like the trick. I mean, you can do that trade. You can trade in several different shapes and forms on several different venues, but they all have different risk characteristics and they all have different funding inefficiencies and these type of things. But that was a great trade. You could do that in Ethereum and it's changing so fast. I mean, now you see it in DeFi and yield farming and staking and stable coin lending. It's a very attractive market. So from a trading perspective with my trading head on, this is just super interesting and I enjoy doing it. As you mentioned two years ago, you're getting 40% annualized from what is a pretty low risk trade, at least in theory. I do think the trade highlights a lot of the implementation considerations that are perhaps unique to the crypto space. Things. For example. example, are you going to implement this with CME futures? Are you going to implement it on a crypto centric centralized exchange like Kraken or FTX and understand their liquidation rules? Are you going to keep things in a hot wallet at the exchange as collateral or cold storage and have to manage your collateral? So I'm hoping maybe you could talk about some of these things and compare and contrast those choices and what makes crypto asset management a little bit unique. I'm happy to do that. I mean, to use, I mean, as you say, the cash and carry trade, this is not something that is new. I mean, you can see this in the crude oil market. I mean, two years ago with that super contango, you're buying crude, you put it on floating storage. That's essentially a cash and carry trade when you sell a futures contract against it. So yes, you can do the cash and carry trade in different ways here as well with the CME. Okay. You know that you're facing the clearing house of the CME. So that's a good thing. That is what I'm used to with my trend following trading program anyways, when I trade the S&P. Or any of these contracts that clear there, that is the same risk, but not every broker at the beginning offered access to Bitcoin and Ethereum futures. And there's also a backed SIBO listed future. I'm actually not sure if that still exists today. It was always the smaller one and the less liquid one, but okay. So you faced the clearing house. Not every broker gives you access. So you need to find the broker that does trade that market. And then the question is, well, how much margin are they requesting for you to put on that trade, especially on a short position, because you will be short the futures contract. And initially they were like, look, this thing can jump a hundred or 200% overnight. So essentially you need to fully collateralize the thing. This means it's very funding inefficient, very capital inefficient to put it up because you also have to fund the spot Bitcoin or the spot Ether lag on another venue. And so you have to pay for one and you have to pay for the other. You have essentially two funded legs. And they don't know of each other. Usually in an efficient market, the spot position would be good collateral against the futures position. And there would be some netting, not to zero, but there would be some netting that takes place that would improve the capital efficiency. And initially that wasn't there. So you had to find ways to make that trade better in order to realize as much of the 40% that you can see on the screen and not lose it all because of funding inefficiencies. And one way of doing that was to say, and initially you could say, look, I have the position in the backed warehouse and the future that clears against backed will recognize that position. So you've got some netting there. Then the margin rates came down and then you can also do it on a crypto venue such as FTX or Binance, or you've mentioned Kraken. And here it's a function of, okay, so what do they accept as collateral? Will they accept a spot Bitcoin position as collateral? Yeah, you find one that does. For instance, FTX does do that. And they would recognize the futures position that you have now on their venue. Obviously they don't recognize the CME position, but you can sell a futures contract or a perpetual swap on FTX. They would know both positions and you would have netting benefits there. But now the risk of that trade also has a different characteristic because you're no longer facing the CME, which is your trusted clearinghouse. You're facing FTX, which is now a, I guess, well-capitalized and, well-funded crypto venue. But back then it wasn't really that large. And you have your position in a hot wallet, not your keys, not your coin. So how much of that yield that you're seeing in the basis is actually fair yield and how much of it is counterparty risk? So you have to think through these dynamics and as always, position size appropriately. With every single trade that you do, it doesn't really matter whether that's an options trade and spoken about that, that you're a crypto trade or a trend following trade, always position size appropriately as small as you can, but not too small because you're also in the business to make money. But you don't want to put all of your, even though that trade looked so appealing, like 40%, I mean, I would not switch off the trend following program and move all the money into that trade just to make 40%. That's a part of my profile.
